## Testing

- Prefer TDD (red/green): write a failing test first, then make it pass
- Always use Playwright CLI to verify website changes
- Avoid logic in test lifecycle hooks — it encourages shared mutable state.
  Prefer fixture factory functions or types, instantiated per test. Make
  fixtures disposable when they need cleanup.

## Shell

- The working directory is ALREADY set to the project root — just run commands directly.
  NEVER prepend `cd`, `pushd`, or `-C` to reach the current working directory.
  This includes ALL equivalent representations of the same path:
  on Windows with Git Bash, `/c/Users/...` and `C:\Users\...` are identical.
  ❌ `cd /c/Users/.../project && command`
  ❌ `git -C /c/Users/.../project status`
  ❌ `pnpm -C . run test`
  ✅ `command` (just run it)
  ✅ `git status`
  ✅ `pnpm run test`
- `-C` and `pushd` are ONLY for commands that target a **different** directory.
  Prefer the tool's `-C` flag (e.g., `git -C other-dir`, `pnpm -C other-dir`)
  over changing directories. Use relative paths for targets within the cwd tree;
  use absolute paths for targets outside it.
- `pnpm -C dir <cmd>` only works for built-in pnpm commands (install, test, run, etc.).
  To run a local binary from a different directory, use `pnpm -C dir exec <tool>`.
- When no `-C` flag is available, use
  `pushd dir && command; rc=$?; popd; exit $rc` instead of `cd dir && command`.
  This ensures the working directory is always restored and the command's exit
  code is preserved.

## MCP Readonly Tools

- **ALWAYS use MCP readonly tools instead of Bash for read-only operations.**
  If the command is covered below, you MUST use the MCP tool — not Bash.
  Fetch the tool schema via `ToolSearch` first if needed; the extra step is not
  optional.
  - `mcp__readonly__git` for: blame, branch, describe, diff, log, ls-files, ls-tree, merge-base, reflog, remote, rev-parse, shortlog, show, stash, status, worktree
  - `mcp__readonly__shell` for: basename, date, dirname, eza, file, jq, ls, pwd, readlink, realpath, stat, wc, which, whoami
  - `mcp__readonly__az` for: devops invoke (GET-only, build-debugging endpoints), devops project/team/extension/service-endpoint/wiki, pipelines list/show/build/release/runs/pool/agent
  - `mcp__readonly__gh` for: api (GET-only: pulls/reviews+reviewers, deployments+environments, check-runs+suites, commits/statuses, compare, contents), attestation verify, cache list, gist list/view, issue list/status/view, label list, pr checks/diff/list/status/view, project field-list/item-list/list/view, release list/view, repo list/view, ruleset check/list/view, run list/view, search code/commits/issues/prs/repos, secret list, status, variable list, workflow list/view
  - `mcp__readonly__chezmoi` for: diff, doctor, managed, source-path, status, target-path, verify
  - `mcp__readonly__acli` for: jira board/filter/project/sprint/workitem list/search/view/comment list
  - `mcp__readonly__npm` for: audit, bin, explain, fund, ls, outdated, root, search, view
  - `mcp__readonly__pnpm` for: audit, bin, licenses list, list, outdated, root, search, store status, why
- NEVER use Bash for a command that is covered by an MCP readonly tool.
  Only fall back to Bash when the command is genuinely not supported.

## GitHub CLI

- Prefer `gh` subcommands over `gh api` for read operations — they're covered
  by the readonly MCP server and don't need Bash. Common replacements:
  - PR comments/reviews: `gh pr view {n} --json comments,reviews`
  - Issue comments: `gh issue view {n} --comments`
  - Run logs: `gh run view {id} --log-failed`
  - PR changed files: `gh pr diff {n}` or `gh pr view {n} --json files`
- `gh api` for read-only endpoints is available via the readonly MCP server
  (path-allowlisted, GET-only). Use it for data the structured CLI doesn't
  expose (e.g., review comments, deployment statuses, check annotations).
- `gh pr view --json comments` only returns issue/conversation comments, NOT
  inline review comments. To read review comments, use:
  `gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls/{n}/comments`
  (available via the readonly MCP server)
- There is no `gh` subcommand for replying to review comment threads. Use `gh api`:
  1. List review comments:
     `gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls/{n}/comments --jq '.[] | "\(.id) \(.path):\(.line) \(.in_reply_to_id)"'`
  1. Find the thread root — the comment where `in_reply_to_id` is null
  1. Reply to the root:
     `gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls/{n}/comments/{root_id}/replies -f body='...'`
- Never use comment IDs from `--json comments` or `--json reviews` when calling
  the review comments API — they are different ID spaces and will 404.

